Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 0e8fc3980a6690d1b2be2b4e96a8018aa1eacc96

This is a really good idea! We have been wanting the D term for a long time.

Please work through the Jenkins errors. Also, can some test cases please be added for these new features?

Hi Josh,
Updated the test case for cycle interval time.

We should probably issue a warning, similar to the above std::cerr usage, if the division does not result in an exact integer. The thermal update interval should always be an exact multiple of the cycle interval.

Hi Josh,
We used ceil() here so that the minimum of thermal update interval would be 1.

OK, that is good that the minimum is 1, however, it is rather subtle. I still would like to see some kind of warning (or perhaps even an error) if this division leaves a remainder (in other words, they are not an exact multiple), as that would often indicate a configuration error, as there is no good reason that I can think of why anybody would want to have the timing not be an exact multiple.

Hi Josh,
I check if updateThermalsTimeMS could be divided by cycleIntervalTimeMS without leaving a remainder here and will print warning message if they are not an exact multiple.
I am curious, why does this need to be added? I don't see any new usage of math functions that weren't there before. Was this missing from earlier?
Thanks. Please mark comments as Resolved, to indicate that you have resolved them.
I don't know enough about the process engineering details of PID loop math, so will leave this to somebody else to review. The code looks syntactically correct, though.
I asked around, and although not perfect (there were some subtleties that are beyond my understanding), this seems good enough to work.

Something wrong here.
zone->getUpdateThermalsCycle() return 1000 by default, but cycleCnt starts counting from 0, which means the cycle of processThermals(zone) is 100 seconds(1000 cycle), not 1 second
Sorry for my misunderstanding. I saw the formula in buildjson.cpp.
Looking better, I still have some unresolved comments though
This should be double, not auto. Otherwise, it will be uint64_t which is already an integer, thus defeating the below check.

This comparison might not work as intended. One thing that might work is to compare updateCount to std::ceil(updateCount) and test for equality. If they are not already equal, then print the warning message and do the assignment, to force them to be equal.
Nice, it looks good now, last chance for any objections from anybody else
I am looking forward to getting the D term

A little bit late, but there's something to note: there's no way to set the D term from the dynamic configuration (dbus/dbusconfiguration). Only from the old static hardcoded JSON file. Another patch should take care of being able to set the D term from the D-Bus configuration.
